et="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/la-and-school-expenditure-2017-to-2018-financial-year</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The table below shows total annual expenditure on residential care across all local authorities in England in 2017-18 across the provision categories defined above.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Total local authority expenditure on residential care by placement provider for 2017-18:</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Own provision </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Private </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Other public </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Voluntary </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total expenditure</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Residential care</strong></p></td><td><p>£410,665,000</p></td><td><p>£866,003,000</p></td><td><p>£12,587,000</p></td><td><p>£34,582,000</p></td><td><p>£1,323,836,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","1682","2019-10-25T11:37:07.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150432/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150432/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-17","Children: Care Homes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the annual cost is of providing residential care to children in (a) local authority-owned homes and (b) privately owned homes.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","1683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150433","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-10-24","<p>The Committee on Climate Change has not provided the Department with an estimate of the costs in each year from 2020 to 2049 for delivering the UK’s net zero target.</p><p> </p><p>Costs are inevitably uncertain between 2020 and 2049 but the CCC estimate that the costs of delivering the net zero target will be equivalent to 1-2% of GDP in 2050. We will publish further detail in the impact assessment for the sixth carbon budget and for all policies which we take forward to deliver the net zero target.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, HM Treasury are carrying out a review into the costs of transitioning to a net zero economy, as recommended by the CCC. The review will consider how to pay for this and how to achieve the transition in a way that works for households, businesses and public finances, as well as how we can ensure this is compatible with plans for a thriving and competitive economy.</p>","Spelthorne","Kwasi  Kwarteng",,"2019-10-24T09:45:34.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150433/answer","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150433/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-10-17","Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether her Department has received from the Committee on Climate Change an estimate of the costs of achieving net zero carbon emissions in each year from 2020 to 2049.","false","Biography information for Graham Stringer","Blackley and Broughton","Graham Stringer","1585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150434","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-24","<p>The Government is committed to securing a deal with the European Union and is working in an energetic and determined way to achieve this.</p><p>The United Kingdom Government has proposed to all Member States that we should maintain existing reciprocal healthcare arrangements, including the S1 scheme, until 31 December 2020 if the UK leaves the EU without a deal. These arrangements would safeguard healthcare for the hundreds of thousands of UK-insured persons who live in Europe.</p><p>I laid a Written Ministerial Statement (<a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2019-09-26/HCWS1832/" target="_blank">HCWS1832</a>) on 26 September 2019, setting out the Department’s progress on ‘no deal’ reciprocal healthcare arrangements, and updated information has been published on GOV.UK and NHS.UK on the situation for each Member State, including what arrangements have been put in place. These pages will be kept updated as further assurances from Member States are received.</p><p> </p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-10-24T14:19:59.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150434/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150434/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","Health Services: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to maintain free health care provision for British citizens living in the EU after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Darren Jones","Bristol North West","Darren Jones","1769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150435","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-10-24","<p>The Committee on Climate Change has not provided the Department with an estimate of the costs in each year from 2020 to 2050 for delivering the UK’s net zero target.</p><p> </p><p>Costs are inevitably uncertain between 2020 and 2049 but the CCC estimate that the costs of delivering the net zero target will be equivalent to 1-2% of GDP in 2050. We will publish further detail in the impact assessment for the sixth carbon budget and for all policies which we take forward to deliver the net zero target.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, HM Treasury are carrying out a review into the costs of transitioning to a net zero economy, as recommended by the CCC. The review will consider how to pay for this and how to achieve the transition in a way that works for households, businesses and public finances, as well as how we can ensure this is compatible with plans for a thriving and competitive economy.</p>","Spelthorne","Kwasi  Kwarteng",,"2019-10-24T09:45:41.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150435/answer","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150435/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-10-17","Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate she has made of the cost to the public purse of achieving net zero carbon emissions by 2050 in each year between 2020 and 2050.","false","Biography information for Graham Stringer","Blackley and Broughton","Graham Stringer","1586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150436","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-22","<p>The Government is committed to supporting young people into work. We aim to ensure that everyone, no matter what their start in life, is given the very best chance of getting into work.</p><p> </p><p>The DWP Youth Obligation Support Programme is currently delivered to young people aged 18-21 making a new claim to Universal Credit. We provide additional tailored support to enable young people to achieve their goals.</p><p> </p><p>In January 2019 we announced the extension of the Mentoring Circles initiative from the ethnic minority community to all young people who could benefit from such support. Mentoring circles support 16-24 year olds by giving them an opportunity to build on their employability skills. By facilitating an interaction with employers this initiative helps to provide young job seekers with access to and interaction with role models in the workplace.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies",,"2019-10-22T16:13:57.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150436/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150436/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-17","Employment: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the final report from the Young people's future health inquiry entitled A healthy foundation for the future published in October 2019, what steps the Government is taking to establish a job market that offers young people secure and rewarding work.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","1603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150437","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-25","<p>​The United Kingdom regards the EU Accession process as fundamental to delivering security, stability and prosperity in the Western Balkans. At the European Council on 17-18 October, the United Kingdom made clear that it was ready to support the opening of EU Accession negotiations with North Macedonia and Albania. We continue to discuss regularly Western Balkan issues with international partners, including France, in bilateral contacts.</p>","Tamworth","Christopher Pincher",,"2019-10-25T11:12:33.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150437/answer","Biography information for Christopher Pincher","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150437/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-17","North Macedonia: EU Enlargement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has made representations to his French counterpart on support for opening EU accession negotiations with the Republic of North Macedonia.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","1725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150438","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-10-22","<p>The Government is aware of concern over the impact of fireworks noise on people and animals. This is why there is already a maximum legal noise level set for fireworks.</p><p> </p><p>The Office for Product Safety and Standards (OPSS) has been working to develop a fact-based evidence base on the key issues that have been raised around fireworks which includes noise levels.</p><p> </p><p>We are receiving representations from a range of stakeholders including members of the public, organisations and charities, representing a range of views. This work will inform current and future policy in this area.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-10-22T08:34:31.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150438/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150438/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-10-17","Fireworks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if she will undertake to (a) review fireworks regulations and (b) reduce the maximum permitted noise level of fireworks.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","1658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150439","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-10-25","<p>Complaints data for 2018/19 can be found in the Ombudsman’s latest annual report and accounts: <a href="https://www.lgo.org.uk/information-centre/about-us/our-performance/lgo-annual-reports" target="_blank">https://www.lgo.org.uk/information-centre/about-us/our-performance/lgo-annual-reports</a>.</p><p>It shows that 2,588 complaints were upheld in 2018/19.</p>","Thornbury and Yate","Luke Hall",,"2019-10-25T13:22:57.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150439/answer","Biography information for Luke Hall","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150439/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-10-17","Local Government and Social Care Ombudsman","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many complaints nationwide were upheld by the Local Government and Social Care Ombudsman in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","1605"
