9,793</p></td><td><p>351</p></td><td><p>293</p></td><td><p>267</p></td><td><p>10,705</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The changes in the number of staff who work at the Environment Agency represent the Spending Review settlements and income received from charge payers.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, please note the following:-</p><p> </p><p>In November 2017 896 FTE transferred to Defra Corporate Services under a Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of Employment) (TUPE) arrangement.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2019-10-22T16:08:53.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150554/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150554/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150554/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-10-17","Environment Agency: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of  the number of Environment Agency FTE staff on (a) temporary and (b) permanent contracts in each year from 2009; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","1655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150555","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-10-22","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Taunton Deane","Rebecca Pow",,"2019-10-22T12:26:44.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150555/answer","Biography information for Rebecca Pow","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150555/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150555/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-10-17","Environment Agency: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the number of site inspections carried out by the Environment Agency in each year since 2014.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","1656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150556","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-24","<p>The United Kingdom Government funded Central Booking System (CBS) has been in operation since March 2018 as a single point of contact for women in Northern Ireland to access abortion care in England. As part of the grant agreement in place with the British Pregnancy Advisory Service the service is delivered to an agreed service specification. The package of care offered to all women includes:</p><p>- a consultation including impartial information/advice, and where needed, counselling with an abortion provider in England. This process will include an assessment of whether the legal grounds for an abortion in England are met;</p><p>- an abortion procedure;</p><p>- HIV and sexually transmitted infection tests; and</p><p>- choice of contraception from the abortion provider</p><p>The CBS, and abortion care provided under the scheme, will continue to offer the same service and care package to women from Northern Ireland to access in England between 22 October 2019 and 31 March 2020, as has been in place since March 2018. The only change is that all travel and, where needed, accommodation is now paid for, without any means testing.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","1548 ; 1549 ; 1552","2019-10-24T10:38:07.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150556/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150556/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150556/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","Abortion: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what guidance the Central Booking Service issued to women in Northern Ireland between the 22 October 2019 and 31 March 2020.","false","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","South Holland and The Deepings","Sir John Hayes","1547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150557","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-24","<p>The United Kingdom Government funded Central Booking System (CBS) has been in operation since March 2018 as a single point of contact for women in Northern Ireland to access abortion care in England. As part of the grant agreement in place with the British Pregnancy Advisory Service the service is delivered to an agreed service specification. The package of care offered to all women includes:</p><p>- a consultation including impartial information/advice, and where needed, counselling with an abortion provider in England. This process will include an assessment of whether the legal grounds for an abortion in England are met;</p><p>- an abortion procedure;</p><p>- HIV and sexually transmitted infection tests; and</p><p>- choice of contraception from the abortion provider</p><p>The CBS, and abortion care provided under the scheme, will continue to offer the same service and care package to women from Northern Ireland to access in England between 22 October 2019 and 31 March 2020, as has been in place since March 2018. The only change is that all travel and, where needed, accommodation is now paid for, without any means testing.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","1547 ; 1549 ; 1552","2019-10-24T10:38:07.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150557/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150557/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150557/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","Abortion: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what support the Central Booking Service plan to provide to women in Northern Ireland that are considering an abortion between 22 October 2019 and 31 March 2020.","false","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","South Holland and The Deepings","Sir John Hayes","1548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150558","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-24","<p>The United Kingdom Government funded Central Booking System (CBS) has been in operation since March 2018 as a single point of contact for women in Northern Ireland to access abortion care in England. As part of the grant agreement in place with the British Pregnancy Advisory Service the service is delivered to an agreed service specification. The package of care offered to all women includes:</p><p>- a consultation including impartial information/advice, and where needed, counselling with an abortion provider in England. This process will include an assessment of whether the legal grounds for an abortion in England are met;</p><p>- an abortion procedure;</p><p>- HIV and sexually transmitted infection tests; and</p><p>- choice of contraception from the abortion provider</p><p>The CBS, and abortion care provided under the scheme, will continue to offer the same service and care package to women from Northern Ireland to access in England between 22 October 2019 and 31 March 2020, as has been in place since March 2018. The only change is that all travel and, where needed, accommodation is now paid for, without any means testing.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","1547 ; 1548 ; 1552","2019-10-24T10:38:07.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150558/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150558/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150558/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","Abortion: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what counselling can be arranged for women from Northern Ireland by the Central Booking Service between 22 October 2019 and 31 March 2020.","false","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","South Holland and The Deepings","Sir John Hayes","1549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150559","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-24","<p>The Northern Ireland Executive was not restored by 21 October 2019, so section 9 of the Northern Ireland (Executive Formation etc) Act has now come into force, providing for the decriminalisation of abortion in Northern Ireland in relation to sections 58 and 59 of the Offences Against the Person Act 1861. The United Kingdom Government is now under a duty to bring forward regulations to introduce a new legal framework for abortion in Northern Ireland by 31 March 2020, and has published guidance for healthcare professionals in Northern Ireland on abortion law for the period 22 October 2019 to 31 March 2020 at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/changes-to-the-law-in-northern-ireland" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/changes-to-the-law-in-northern-ireland</a></p><p>This makes clear that abortion services are not expected to be routinely available in Northern Ireland before 31 March 2020.</p><p>The UK Government-funded Central Booking System (CBS) has been in operation since March 2018 as a single point of contact for women in Northern Ireland to access abortion care in England. The CBS, and abortion care provided under the scheme, will continue to offer the same service and care package to women from Northern Ireland between 22 October 2019 and 31 March 2020. During this period women from Northern Ireland will be able to have all travel and, where needed, accommodation paid for without any means testing.</p><p>The package of care offered to women from Northern Ireland is equivalent to the package of care offered to women from England and includes:</p><p>- a consultation including impartial information/advice, and where needed, counselling with an abortion provider in England. This process will include an assessment of whether the legal grounds for an abortion in England are met;</p><p>- an abortion procedure;</p><p>- HIV and sexually transmitted infection tests; and</p><p>- choice of contraception from the abortion provider.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","1551","2019-10-24T14:28:36.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150559/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150559/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150559/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","Abortion: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether women from Northern Ireland considering an abortion are able to receive a similar level of counselling as women in England and Wales between 22 October 2019 and March 2020.","false","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","South Holland and The Deepings","Sir John Hayes","1550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150560","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-24","<p>The Northern Ireland Executive was not restored by 21 October 2019, so section 9 of the Northern Ireland (Executive Formation etc) Act has now come into force, providing for the decriminalisation of abortion in Northern Ireland in relation to sections 58 and 59 of the Offences Against the Person Act 1861. The United Kingdom Government is now under a duty to bring forward regulations to introduce a new legal framework for abortion in Northern Ireland by 31 March 2020, and has published guidance for healthcare professionals in Northern Ireland on abortion law for the period 22 October 2019 to 31 March 2020 at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/changes-to-the-law-in-northern-ireland" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/changes-to-the-law-in-northern-ireland</a></p><p>This makes clear that abortion services are not expected to be routinely available in Northern Ireland before 31 March 2020.</p><p>The UK Government-funded Central Booking System (CBS) has been in operation since March 2018 as a single point of contact for women in Northern Ireland to access abortion care in England. The CBS, and abortion care provided under the scheme, will continue to offer the same service and care package to women from Northern Ireland between 22 October 2019 and 31 March 2020. During this period women from Northern Ireland will be able to have all travel and, where needed, accommodation paid for without any means testing.</p><p>The package of care offered to women from Northern Ireland is equivalent to the package of care offered to women from England and includes:</p><p>- a consultation including impartial information/advice, and where needed, counselling with an abortion provider in England. This process will include an assessment of whether the legal grounds for an abortion in England are met;</p><p>- an abortion procedure;</p><p>- HIV and sexually transmitted infection tests; and</p><p>- choice of contraception from the abortion provider.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","1550","2019-10-24T14:28:36.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150560/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150560/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150560/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","Abortion: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether there is a difference in the (a) guidance, (b) support, and (c) counselling made available to women in (i) Northern Ireland and (ii) England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","South Holland and The Deepings","Sir John Hayes","1551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150561","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-24","<p>The United Kingdom Government funded Central Booking System (CBS) has been in operation since March 2018 as a single point of contact for women in Northern Ireland to access abortion care in England. As part of the grant agreement in place with the British Pregnancy Advisory Service the service is delivered to an agreed service specification. The package of care offered to all women includes:</p><p>- a consultation including impartial information/advice, and where needed, counselling with an abortion provider in England. This process will include an assessment of whether the legal grounds for an abortion in England are met;</p><p>- an abortion procedure;</p><p>- HIV and sexually transmitted infection tests; and</p><p>- choice of contraception from the abortion provider</p><p>The CBS, and abortion care provided under the scheme, will continue to offer the same service and care package to women from Northern Ireland to access in England between 22 October 2019 and 31 March 2020, as has been in place since March 2018. The only change is that all travel and, where needed, accommodation is now paid for, without any means testing.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","1547 ; 1548 ; 1549","2019-10-24T10:38:07.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150561/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150561/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150561/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","Abortion: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps the Government has taken to ensure that the Central Booking Service will provide impartial advice to women from Northern Ireland between 22 October 2019 and 31 March 2020.","false","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","South Holland and The Deepings","Sir John Hayes","1552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150562","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-24","<p>Guidance issued by professional bodies is a matter for each individual organisation. The Government has published its own guidance for healthcare professionals in Northern Ireland on abortion law in the period 22 October 2019 to 31 March 2020, which is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/changes-to-the-law-in-northern-ireland" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/changes-to-the-law-in-northern-ireland</a></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-10-24T15:12:20.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150562/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150562/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150562/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","Abortion: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to ensure that abortion guidelines issued by professional bodies in Northern Ireland will be the same as guidelines issued by professional bodies in England and Wales between 22 October 2019 and 31 March 2020.","false","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","South Holland and The Deepings","Sir John Hayes","1553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150563","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-10-25","<p>I published guidance for health professionals on 7 October 2019 on gov.uk/nio that sets out the changes to the law on access to abortion services for healthcare professionals and what this means for them in relation to their patients during the interim period.</p><p> </p><p>No healthcare professionals will be compelled to provide services, other than treatment which is necessary to save the life of the woman or girl, or to prevent grave permanent injury to her physical or mental health. In the interim period (prior to the legal framework coming into force by 31 March 2020) if a healthcare professional has a conscientious objection to abortion, they can raise this with their employer and follow relevant guidance from their professional body.</p><p> </p><p>We will be shortly consulting on the new legal framework. We will continue engaging with healthcare professionals in Northern Ireland to ensure that the legal abortion provisions can also be accompanied by professional guidance and professional standards of practice to assist healthcare professionals in Northern Ireland to clearly understand their legal rights, obligations and duties from 31 March 2020.</p><p> </p>","Skipton and Ripon","Julian Smith",,"2019-10-25T13:59:02.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150563/answer","Biography information for Julian Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150563/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150563/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2019-10-17","Abortion: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what legal protections in place between 22 October 2019 and 31 March 2020 to protect health professionals in Northern Ireland that have a conscientious objection to abortion.","false","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","South Holland and The Deepings","Sir John Hayes","1554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150564","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-22","<p>NHS Digital and NHS England publishes annual accident and emergency (A&amp;E) activity in National Health Service hospitals at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://digital.nhs.uk/data-and-information/publications/statistical/hospital-accident--emergency-activity/2018-19" target="_blank">https://digital.nhs.uk/data-and-information/publications/statistical/hospital-accident--emergency-activity/2018-19</a></p><p>The percentage of patient attendances spending four hours or less in A&amp;E, 2009-10 to 2018-19 can be found in the following table.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>% 4 Hours or Less</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>98.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>97.4%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>96.6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>95.9%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>95.7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>93.6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>91.9%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>89.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>88.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018-19</p></td><td><p>88.0%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: NHS England and NHS Digital</p><p> </p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-10-22T11:18:49.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150564/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150564/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150564/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","Accident and Emergency Departments: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what proportion of patients were seen within four hours in A&E in (a) 2018-19 and (b) each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","1672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150565","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-22","<p>A monthly collection of waiting times for National Health Service audiology assessments is available on the NHS England website, which records the number of people waiting for more than six weeks at the end of each month. The monthly data is attached. The data includes waiting times for a first assessment or subsequent reassessment. The data is not broken down by type of assessment.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-10-22T17:29:31.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150565/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150565/answer","PQ1673 audiology assessment waiting time formatted table.xlsx","PQ1673 audiology assessment waiting time formatted table.xlsx","PQ1673 table","PQ1673 table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150565/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","Hearing: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many patients waited more than six weeks for (a) an initial NHS hearing assessment and (b) a follow-up NHS hearing aid assessment in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","1673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150566","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-22","<p>The National Health Service has set a standard maximum wait of six weeks from referral to out-patient investigations such as echocardiograms.</p><p>The NHS Long Term Plan will ensure that an additional 54,000 people with heart failure or valvular heart disease will be detected and diagnosed. It will also ensure optimisation of management and treatment of patients admitted to hospital.</p><p>In addition, the Getting It Right First Time cardiothoracic surgery report has identified activity and financial opportunities to reduce waiting times for urgent coronary artery bypass grafting.</p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill",,"2019-10-22T16:52:46.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150566/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150566/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150566/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","Heart Diseases: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent steps his Department has taken to reduce waiting times for the treatment of chronic heart disease.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","1674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150567","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-22","<p>The number of patients waiting over 52 weeks for treatment in August 2019 was 1,233. This figure includes all incomplete referral pathways regardless of the source of referral.</p><p>NHS England publishes Referral-to-Treatment performance data on a monthly basis, including the numbers of patients waiting over 52 weeks for treatment following referral.</p><p>This is available via the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/rtt-waiting-times/rtt-data-2019-20/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/rtt-waiting-times/rtt-data-2019-20/</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-10-22T15:33:09.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150567/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150567/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150567/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","Hospitals: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many people have waited longer that 52 weeks from GP referral to treatment in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","1675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150568","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-22","<p>The Government continues to engage regularly with the Mexican authorities at Ministerial, official and state levels to discuss human rights, including Freedom of Religion or Belief (FoRB), and to support a broad human rights agenda in the country. During the Foreign Secretary's first visit to Mexico in August 2019, he raised human rights with his counterpart Foreign Minister Marcelo Ebrard, who expressed his support for working with us bilaterally and multilaterally to protect human rights. Baroness Williams also raised FoRB with Mexican Interior Minister in September 2019. I have also spoken to Deputy Foreign Minister Ventura. At the UN Universal Periodic Review session in November 2018 the United Kingdom made recommendations regarding accountability for human rights violations and addressing impunity for violence against human rights defenders.</p>","Tamworth","Christopher Pincher",,"2019-10-22T13:25:34.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150568/answer","Biography information for Christopher Pincher","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150568/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150568/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-17","Mexico: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to the Government of Mexico to improve protective measures for (a) religious leaders and (b) other human rights defenders.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","1775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150569","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-11-05","<p>A dedicated Departmental Operations Centre (DOC) will manage and lead preparations in the event of a no-deal Brexit. Staff working in the DOC will also manage work associated with the UK's exit from the EU in any other scenario. We do not routinely separately record no-deal work from other Brexit work. MHCLG’s normal operations include some out of hours working alongside standard daytime working hours. <br> <br> To support this pattern, we currently estimate the Department will require approximately 200 FTE, using a mix of grades but coming mainly from HEO and Grade 7 staff. This estimate will be subject to on-going review to ensure it reflects any change in circumstances or requirements</p><p><br></p><p> </p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2019-11-05T14:52:03.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150569/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150569/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150569/answer","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150569/answer/previousversion/1032","Biography information for Jake Berry","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-10-17","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many staff at which grades his Department requires to undertake work on leaving the EU without an agreement in the Departmental Operations Centre during standard daytime working hours.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","1664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150570","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-24","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill",,"2019-10-24T15:48:14.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150570/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150570/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150570/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","HIV Infection: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many men have contracted HIV while waiting to be placed on the PrEP impact trial.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","1684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150571","Treasury","false","2019-10-25","<p>Total wine duty for the first quarter of 2018-19 and 2019-20 are £1086m and £1061m respectively.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the amount of excise duty collected on wine, is are routinely published online by HM Revenue &amp; Customs.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/alcohol-bulletin" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/alcohol-bulletin</a></p><p> </p><p>The Wine duty rates were increased on the 1st February 2019. An assessment of the impact of this measure on an annual basis was published at budget 2018 and can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/increase-in-alcohol-duty-rates/alcohol-duty-uprating" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/increase-in-alcohol-duty-rates/alcohol-duty-uprating</a></p>","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Mr Simon Clarke","1686","2019-10-25T07:40:36.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150571/answer","Biography information for Mr Simon Clarke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150571/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150571/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-17","Wines: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much the Treasury received in wine duty receipts for the first quarter of (a) 2018-19 and (b) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","1685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150572","Treasury","false","2019-10-25","<p>Total wine duty for the first quarter of 2018-19 and 2019-20 are £1086m and £1061m respectively.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the amount of excise duty collected on wine, is are routinely published online by HM Revenue &amp; Customs.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/alcohol-bulletin" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/alcohol-bulletin</a></p><p> </p><p>The Wine duty rates were increased on the 1st February 2019. An assessment of the impact of this measure on an annual basis was published at budget 2018 and can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/increase-in-alcohol-duty-rates/alcohol-duty-uprating" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/increase-in-alcohol-duty-rates/alcohol-duty-uprating</a></p>","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Mr Simon Clarke","1685","2019-10-25T07:40:36.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150572/answer","Biography information for Mr Simon Clarke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150572/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150572/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-17","Wines: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what comparative assessment he has made of wine duty receipts for the first quarters of 2018-19 and 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","1686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150573","Treasury","false","2019-10-22","<p>Wine duty was last reduced in 1984. Both beer duty and spirits were last reduced in 2015.</p>","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Mr Simon Clarke",,"2019-10-22T11:23:18.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150573/answer","Biography information for Mr Simon Clarke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150573/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150573/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-17","Alcoholic Drinks: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, when excise duty was last reduced for (a) wine, (b) beer and (c) spirits.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","1687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150574","Treasury","false","2019-10-25","<p>Information on the amount of excise duty collected on alcohol, and the rates of the various duties are routinely published online by HM Revenue &amp; Customs. This also includes information about the increase in excise duty from 2010 to 2015. This can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/alcohol-bulletin" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/alcohol-bulletin</a></p>","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Mr Simon Clarke",,"2019-10-25T07:33:00.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150574/answer","Biography information for Mr Simon Clarke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150574/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150574/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-17","Alcoholic Drinks: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the increase in excise duty was for (a) wine, (b) beer and (c) spirits from 2010 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","1688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150575","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-10-23","<p>The Ministry of Justice conducts regular equality impact assessments on all proposed pay and policy changes and implementation. The MoJ operates a pay and grading structure where pay is defined by job weight and content.</p><p> </p><p>HMPPS is responsible for preparing and submitting the Government’s annual evidence on Prison Officer’s pay to the independent Prison Service Pay Review Body. As part of this process, HMPPS looks at all equality issues based on the proposals and monitor the diversity of the remit group from available data. A full review was conducted in 2012 which resulted in the introduction of a new pay and grading structure and new ways of working (Fair and Sustainable) for Prison Officer grades. Fair and Sustainable was introduced to support pay equality, with salary determined by the requirements of the role based on the Job description.</p><p> </p><p>An Equality Impact Assessment on pay in the National Probation Service was carried out in September 2018 as part of a project to reform its pay structure.</p>","Croydon South","Chris Philp",,"2019-10-23T15:51:35.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150575/answer","Biography information for Chris Philp","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150575/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150575/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-17","Ministry of Justice: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many equal pay reviews there have been in his Department since 2010; what the dates were of those reviews; and whether his Department plans to undertake an equal pay review in 2019.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","1726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150576","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-24","<p>An Equal Pay Review was undertaken in 2015. An external service provider has been appointed to undertake a further Review, with work expected to be completed before the end of 2019.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-10-24T14:13:24.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150576/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150576/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150576/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-17","Department for Transport: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many equal pay reviews there have been in his Department since 2010; what the dates were of those reviews; and whether his Department plans to undertake an equal pay review in 2019.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","1727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150577","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-10-22","<p>Since 2010, Defra has undertaken two equal pay reviews. These were in April 2010 and February 2015. Defra is currently undertaking an equal pay review, and this should be completed in 2019.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2019-10-22T16:03:12.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150577/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150577/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150577/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-10-17","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many equal pay reviews there have been in her Department since 2010; what the dates were of those reviews; and whether her Department plans to undertake an equal pay review in 2019.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","1728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150578","Home Office","false","2019-10-22","<p>The Home Office conducts a Policy Equality Statement (PES) annually, following the annual pay award process. The process is usually finalised in the Autumn further to negotiations with Trade Unions. A Policy Equality Statement (PES) will be undertaken following the implementation of the Pay Award this year.</p><p>Additionally, since 2017 the Home Office has annually published its gender pay gap on GOV.UK.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/home-office-gender-pay-gap-report-and-data-2017/home-offices-gender-pay-gap-report-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/home-office-gender-pay-gap-report-and-data-2017/home-offices-gender-pay-gap-report-2017</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/home-office-gender-pay-gap-report-and-data-2018/home-offices-gender-pay-gap-report-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/home-office-gender-pay-gap-report-and-data-2018/home-offices-gender-pay-gap-report-2018</a></p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2019-10-22T15:31:45.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150578/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150578/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150578/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-17","Home Office: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many equal pay reviews there have been in her Department since 2010; what the dates were of those reviews; and whether her Department plans to undertake an equal pay review in 2019.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","1729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150579","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-22","<p>Officials in the British Embassy in Mexico City have regular contact with the Government of Mexico and civil society groups, including Christian Solidarity Worldwide, to help inform our understanding of the human rights situation on the ground, including in matters of Freedom of Religion or Relief (FoRB). We work closely with the Government of Mexico to support a broad human rights agenda. The Foreign Secretary's visit to Mexico in August 2019 offered the opportunity to discuss human rights with his Mexican counterpart and we welcomed their commitment to address the challenges. Baroness Williams raised FoRB with Mexican Interior Minister in September 2019. I have also spoken to my counterpart, Deputy Foreign Minister Ventura. The Mexican Government, the local UN Human Rights office and local civil society organisations assess that FORB violations are not widespread or endemic, although they do accept there are local incidences of people being affected because of their religious belief.</p>","Tamworth","Christopher Pincher",,"2019-10-22T13:30:54.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150579/answer","Biography information for Christopher Pincher","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150579/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150579/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-17","Mexico: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Mexican counterpart on religious freedom in Mexico; and what assessment he has made of the attitude in that country towards repeat perpetrators of violence against religious freedom in the communities of (a) Cuamontax del Huazalingo and (b) Mesa Limuntitla in the state of Hidalgo and (c) other parts of Mexico.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","1776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150580","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-22","<p>DWP is committed to providing services which embrace diversity and which promote equality of opportunity. As an employer, we are also committed to equality and valuing diversity within our workforce. Our goal is to ensure that these commitments are embedded in our day to day working practices with all our customers, colleagues and partners.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is legally required to consider the impact of our policies and processes on people who share a protected characteristic, and to document our findings in order that we can provide evidence on this if challenged. The Equality Act does not specify a prescribed Equality Analysis process, however, since 2010 we have completed department wide Equal Pay Audits for 2011, 2014 and 2016. These were completed in 2012, 2016 and 2018 retrospectively. A further review is scheduled for 2019.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p />","Eastleigh","Mims Davies",,"2019-10-22T16:11:39.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150580/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150580/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150580/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-17","Department for Work and Pensions: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many equal pay reviews there have been in her Department since 2010; what the dates were of those reviews; and whether her Department plans to undertake an equal pay review in 2019.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","1730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150581","Treasury","false","2019-10-22","In line with Government policy, HMRC’s Equal Pay Audit is produced every three years. Since 2010, Equal Pay Audits have been conducted for 2013 (published November 2015) and 2016 (published December 2018). HMRC are currently working on the 2019 Equal Pay Audit which will be published in due course.","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2019-10-22T15:17:11.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150581/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150581/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150581/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-17","Equal Pay: Reviews","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many equal pay reviews there have been in HMRC since 2010; what the dates were of those reviews; and whether HMRC plans to undertake an equal pay review in 2019.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","1731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150582","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-24","<p>Officials have begun discussions with the Departmental Trade Unions on making the relevant changes. Future meetings will include the Unite Union, who represent drivers in the Government Car Service.</p><p> </p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-10-24T14:00:52.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150582/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150582/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150582/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-17","Department for Transport: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the pay system in his Department has been changed to take account of the Employment Appeal Tribunal ruling on Dudley Metropolitan Borough Council v Mr G Willetts and Others on holiday pay and voluntary overtime; and whether affected workers in his Department have been given back pay as a result of that ruling.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","1732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150583","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-22","<p>Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is currently provided in England through the three year PrEP Impact Trial. Participation in the trial is on a voluntary basis and it is for clinics and local authorities to decide the number of allocated places they can accept.</p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill",,"2019-10-22T16:49:53.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150583/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150583/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150583/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","HIV Infection: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to ensure that London councils are adequately resourced to deliver the additional 40 per cent of places allocated to them in January 2019 for the PrEP Impact Trial.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","1689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150584","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-10-22","<p>The Ministry of Justice (HMPPS, HMCTS, CICA, LAA, and OPG) pay system has been updated in response to the tribunal case to meet the requirement for holiday pay and overtime. Affected staff have received arrears backdated to 1 March 2016.</p>","Croydon South","Chris Philp",,"2019-10-22T14:52:21.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150584/answer","Biography information for Chris Philp","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150584/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150584/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-10-17","Ministry of Justice: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the pay system in his Department has been changed to take account of the Employment Appeal Tribunal ruling on Dudley Metropolitan Borough Council v Mr G Willetts and Others on holiday pay and voluntary overtime; and whether affected workers in his Department have been given back pay as a result of that ruling.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","1733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150585","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-10-29","<p>Following the Tribunal ruling, Defra made backdated payments to eligible staff and is currently working with a number of other Government Departments to change the pay system for the future.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2019-10-29T12:23:34.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150585/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150585/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150585/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-10-17","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether the pay system in her Department has been changed to take account of the Employment Appeal Tribunal ruling on Dudley Metropolitan Borough Council v Mr G Willetts and Others on holiday pay and voluntary overtime; and whether affected workers in her Department have been given back pay as a result of that ruling.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","1734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150586","Home Office","false","2019-10-30","<p>The Home Office currently has a form of Holiday Pay allowance built into the pay system. The Home Office is aware of the Employment Appeal Tribunal referred to in the Question, and the implications for our approach to pay. The Department has signalled to the Trades Unions in Summer 2019 that it intends to open negotiations on this subject later in 2019. Decisions on back pay will be taken as part of the negotiations process.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2019-10-30T17:24:23.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150586/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150586/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150586/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-17","Home Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the pay system in her Department has been changed to take account of the Employment Appeal Tribunal ruling on Dudley Metropolitan Borough Council v Mr G Willetts and Others on holiday pay and voluntary overtime; and whether affected workers in her Department have been given back pay as a result of that ruling.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","1735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150587","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-23","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions is currently developing a policy to account for the rulings related to holiday pay and voluntary overtime. As this policy is still in development, no payments have been made.</p><p /><p><strong> </strong></p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies",,"2019-10-23T09:51:24.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150587/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150587/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150587/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-17","Department for Work and Pensions: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the pay system in her Department has been changed to take account of the Employment Appeal Tribunal ruling on Dudley Metropolitan Borough Council v Mr G Willetts and Others on holiday pay and voluntary overtime; and whether affected workers in her Department have been given back pay as a result of that ruling.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","1736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150588","Treasury","false","2019-10-22","<p>HMRC have been following the guidance issued by Civil Service Employee Policy (CSEP) following this judgment. It is the responsibility of Departments to implement changes to their policy and contract framework, and HMRC are awaiting guidance due shortly from CSEP to support HMRC in doing so.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC have made a business case to Treasury to ask for pay flexibility to allow HMRC to negotiate a new pay and reward framework with the trade unions. HMRC are planning to implement these changes from June next year and will make back payments where applicable. HMRC have not made any payments specifically following the ruling.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2019-10-22T15:29:02.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150588/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150588/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150588/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-17","Treasury: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the pay system in HMRC has been changed to take account of the Employment Appeal Tribunal ruling on Dudley Metropolitan Borough Council v Mr G Willetts and Others on holiday pay and voluntary overtime; and whether affected workers in HMRC have been given back pay as a result of that ruling.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","1737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150609","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-28","<p>We remain concerned about continuing reports of discrimination against religious minorities in Pakistan. The Government strongly condemns the persecution of all minorities, including the targeting of innocent people based on their beliefs. We regularly raise our concerns about the use of the blasphemy laws with the Pakistani Government at a senior level. The British Government continues to urge Pakistan to honour its human rights obligations, including those related to religious minorities, and to uphold the rule of law.</p><p>​</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-10-28T12:49:09.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150609/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150609/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150609/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-17","Pakistan: Minority Groups","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the joint report by the APPG for the Pakistani Minorities and the APPG for International Freedom of Religion or Belief Religious minorities of Pakistan: report of a parliamentary visit, published on 9 September.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150610","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Official Receiver’s duty is to realise assets to maximise returns to creditors. This involves selling viable parts of the Thomas Cook business, any discussions remain confidential between the Official Receiver and interested parties.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Government is not involved in decision making in relation to the allocation of airport slots.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Vere of Norbiton","HL187","2019-10-31T13:47:10.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150610/answer","Biography information for Baroness Vere of Norbiton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150610/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-17","Thomas Cook: Insolvency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking, if any, to ensure that there is a competitive and fair purchasing process for Thomas Cook's former airline routes.","false","Biography information for Baroness Doocey",,"Baroness Doocey","HL186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150611","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Official Receiver’s duty is to realise assets to maximise returns to creditors. This involves selling viable parts of the Thomas Cook business, any discussions remain confidential between the Official Receiver and interested parties.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Government is not involved in decision making in relation to the allocation of airport slots.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Vere of Norbiton","HL186","2019-10-31T13:47:10.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150611/answer","Biography information for Baroness Vere of Norbiton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150611/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-17","Thomas Cook: Insolvency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking, if any, to ensure that there is a competitive and fair purchasing process for Thomas Cook's former landing and take-off slots at Gatwick Airport.","false","Biography information for Baroness Doocey",,"Baroness Doocey","HL187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150612","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-31","<p>The costs of the repatriation are not yet finalised, but we are seeking to minimise the impact on government and taxpayers by recovering costs where appropriate through the ATOL scheme, credit card companies and travel insurance.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC does not comment on the tax affairs of identifiable businesses.</p>",,"Baroness Vere of Norbiton",,"2019-10-31T15:06:16.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150612/answer","Biography information for Baroness Vere of Norbiton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150612/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-17","Thomas Cook: Insolvency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what estimate they have made of the costs to the public arising from the collapse of Thomas Cook as a result of (1) the repatriation of passengers, and (2) the loss of tax revenues received from the company.","false","Biography information for Baroness Doocey",,"Baroness Doocey","HL188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150613","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-31","<p>It is the responsibility of directors to decide when a business is no longer a going concern. It is not the role of government to decide on the viability of a business.</p><p> </p><p>As part of its duty to protect consumers, the CAA closely monitors tour operators and airlines through its management of the ATOL scheme and has strong working relationships with the UK travel sector.</p><p> </p><p>Now that the repatriation operation is complete, our efforts will be focused on ensuring that reforms are brought forward, taking into account the lessons learned from both the Thomas Cook and Monarch failures.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Vere of Norbiton","HL190","2019-10-31T13:45:37.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150613/answer","Biography information for Baroness Vere of Norbiton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150613/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-17","Tour Operators: Insolvency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, following the collapse of Thomas Cook, what steps they intend to take, if any, to help protect tour operators from bankruptcies.","false","Biography information for Baroness Doocey",,"Baroness Doocey","HL189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150614","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-31","<p>It is the responsibility of directors to decide when a business is no longer a going concern. It is not the role of government to decide on the viability of a business.</p><p> </p><p>As part of its duty to protect consumers, the CAA closely monitors tour operators and airlines through its management of the ATOL scheme and has strong working relationships with the UK travel sector.</p><p> </p><p>Now that the repatriation operation is complete, our efforts will be focused on ensuring that reforms are brought forward, taking into account the lessons learned from both the Thomas Cook and Monarch failures.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Vere of Norbiton","HL189","2019-10-31T13:45:37.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150614/answer","Biography information for Baroness Vere of Norbiton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150614/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-17","Airlines: Insolvency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, following the collapse of Thomas Cook, what steps they intend to take, if any, to help airlines mitigate risks of bankruptcy.","false","Biography information for Baroness Doocey",,"Baroness Doocey","HL190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150615","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has written to the Financial Reporting Council to ensure they prioritise, as a matter of urgency, an investigation into both the causes of the company’s failure and the conduct of its directors.</p><p> </p><p>The FRC will conduct a robust investigation into the preparation of the company’s accounts in compliance with these standards and seek areas where lessons may be learned.</p><p> </p><p>Thomas Cook Group prepared their accounts using EU-adopted International Financial Reporting Standards, which are set by the International Accounting Standards Board and used in 125 countries worldwide.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Vere of Norbiton",,"2019-10-31T13:49:13.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150615/answer","Biography information for Baroness Vere of Norbiton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150615/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-17","Thomas Cook: Insolvency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to conduct a review of the collapse of Thomas Cook; and if so, to what timescale.","false","Biography information for Baroness Doocey",,"Baroness Doocey","HL191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150616","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Department for Transport has invested £210 million in the Cycle Ambition Cities programme, which to date has delivered 155 miles of new segregated cycle routes, 186 miles of new on-road and off-road routes for cyclists and pedestrians, and 136 miles of off-road cycling signage and resurfacing improvements across eight cities. The Department has also recently announced investment of £22 million to upgrade 32 routes, totalling 103 miles, along the National Cycle Network (NCN) to improve connectivity, accessibility and increase functional journeys.</p>",,"Baroness Vere of Norbiton",,"2019-10-31T13:44:14.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150616/answer","Biography information for Baroness Vere of Norbiton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150616/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150616/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-17","Cycleways","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they have taken to improve and extend the cycle network since the publication of their Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy in 2017.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150617","Home Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>Police have powers under the Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 and Common Law to seize and retain property that is believed to be evidence of an offence.</p><p>Once seized, the property may be retained for no longer than is necessary for use as evidence at a trial, for forensic examination or for investigation in connection with an offence or to establish the rightful owner of the property. To ensure the property is admissible as evidence, police need to keep an accurate record of its seizure and retention and safe keeping to establish the chain of evidence.</p><p>Owners may obtain independent legal advice if they wish to make a claim against police for damage to their property. Free advice can be sought from a Law Centre or Citizens Advice (CA). If a person wishes to claim property seized by the police, they may also apply to a magistrate’s court under the Police (Property) Act 1897 for its possession.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL194","2019-11-05T17:56:21.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150617/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150617/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-17","Demonstrations: Seized Articles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government under what powers the police may confiscate camping equipment, food, solar panels, portable lavatories and litter bins, which are being stored in connection with planned demonstrations; and whether the police are required to keep a record of such items that are seized, and to store them in appropriate conditions.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150618","Home Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>Police have powers under the Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 and Common Law to seize and retain property that is believed to be evidence of an offence.</p><p>Once seized, the property may be retained for no longer than is necessary for use as evidence at a trial, for forensic examination or for investigation in connection with an offence or to establish the rightful owner of the property. To ensure the property is admissible as evidence, police need to keep an accurate record of its seizure and retention and safe keeping to establish the chain of evidence.</p><p>Owners may obtain independent legal advice if they wish to make a claim against police for damage to their property. Free advice can be sought from a Law Centre or Citizens Advice (CA). If a person wishes to claim property seized by the police, they may also apply to a magistrate’s court under the Police (Property) Act 1897 for its possession.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL193","2019-11-05T17:56:21.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150618/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150618/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-17","Demonstrations: Seized Articles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether there is any recourse for the owners of items that are damaged when the police remove them from the site of demonstrations; and whether the owners of such items can reclaim them from the police.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150619","Treasury","false","2019-10-29","<p>All taxes are kept under review and the impact of a change to alcohol duty is considered at each fiscal event, including its effect on jobs and the wider economy. HMRC publishes a Tax Information Impact Note explaining the impact of the change, each time a duty rate is amended.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"The Earl of Courtown","HL196","2019-10-29T15:41:57.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150619/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150619/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-17","Alcoholic Drinks: Excise Duties","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the report by the Fraser of Allander Institute Economic Perspectives: Could a reduction in alcohol consumption be good news for the UK economy?, published in June 2018, in particular its finding that an increase in alcohol taxes could boost national income and create 17,000 jobs; and what steps, if any, they intend to take in response to that finding.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150620","Treasury","false","2019-10-29","<p>All taxes are kept under review and the impact of a change to alcohol duty is considered at each fiscal event, including its effect on jobs and the wider economy. HMRC publishes a Tax Information Impact Note explaining the impact of the change, each time a duty rate is amended.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"The Earl of Courtown","HL195","2019-10-29T15:41:57.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150620/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150620/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-17","Alcoholic Drinks: Excise Duties","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the impact of raising alcohol duty on Her Majesty's Treasury’s income.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150621","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Government is very clear about the dangers that alcohol poses to the unborn child and reflects this in the advice it gives. The United Kingdom Chief Medical Officers’ low risk drinking guidelines published in 2016 provide clear advice to women not to drink alcohol if they are planning for a pregnancy or are pregnant. The National Health Service online information also reflects this advice.</p><p>Additionally, the Government has been clear that the alcohol industry must reflect the UK Chief Medical Officers' alcohol guidelines on the labels of their products which includes a no drinking in pregnancy logo.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England, NHS England and local commissioners are already undertaking awareness and education on the dangers of drinking alcohol while pregnant.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","HL198","2019-10-31T14:15:18.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150621/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150621/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","Pregnancy: Alcoholic Drinks","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the research by the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine Pregnancy, Fertility, Breastfeeding, and Alcohol Consumption: An Analysis of Framing and Completeness of Information Disseminated by Alcohol Industry–Funded Organizations, published on 13 October, which found that the information provided by alcohol industry-funded organisations is misleading about the risks to pregnant women of consuming alcohol, what steps they intend to take to ensure that pregnant women are given accurate information about such risks.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150622","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Government is very clear about the dangers that alcohol poses to the unborn child and reflects this in the advice it gives. The United Kingdom Chief Medical Officers’ low risk drinking guidelines published in 2016 provide clear advice to women not to drink alcohol if they are planning for a pregnancy or are pregnant. The National Health Service online information also reflects this advice.</p><p>Additionally, the Government has been clear that the alcohol industry must reflect the UK Chief Medical Officers' alcohol guidelines on the labels of their products which includes a no drinking in pregnancy logo.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England, NHS England and local commissioners are already undertaking awareness and education on the dangers of drinking alcohol while pregnant.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","HL197","2019-10-31T14:15:18.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150622/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150622/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150622/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","Pregnancy: Alcoholic Drinks","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the research by the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine Pregnancy, Fertility, Breastfeeding, and Alcohol Consumption: An Analysis of Framing and Completeness of Information Disseminated by Alcohol Industry–Funded Organizations, published on 13 October, what plans they have to make warnings of the risks of consuming alcohol in pregnancy mandatory.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150623","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Government has worked with industry to ensure that alcohol labels reflect the United Kingdom Chief Medical Officer’s Low Risk Drinking Guidelines for drinks produced after 1 September 2019. The industry has committed to comply with this requirement. Local trading standards have powers to remove products manufactured after 1 September 2019, where those products have labels which include the old guidelines. Stock produced before 1 September 2019 can be sold through.</p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford",,"2019-10-31T14:15:53.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150623/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150623/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","Alcoholic Drinks: Labelling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they plan to take to ensure that they meet the deadline to remove the out-of-date Chief Medical Officer’s guidelines from alcohol product labels.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150624","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-29","<p>We are aware of allegations of use of white phosphorus but are not aware of any reports of flechettes being used. Allegations that white phosphorus has been used against civilians are extremely worrying and it is important that the full facts are established. We have called on all parties to uphold international humanitarian law which prohibits attacks against civilians irrespective of the weapon used. We have not seen any evidence to suggest that detention camps have been targeted by Turkish forces with a view to freeing Daesh fighters. Turkey is a member of the Global Coalition and has demonstrated its commitment to the ongoing fight against Daesh.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-10-29T12:05:19.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150624/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150624/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-17","Syria: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have received any evidence of the recent use by Turkey in northern Syria of (1) white phosphorus in gas or solid form, and (2) flechettes; and whether there is any evidence to suggest that detention camps have been targeted by Turkish forces with a view to freeing ISIS fighters.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150625","Home Office","false","2019-11-04","<p>The Government provides a number of schemes that offer a safe and legal route to the UK for the most vulnerable refugees. In total, the UK provided protection to over 7,000 children in the year ending June 2019, and 39,500 since the start of 2010, and in every year since 2016, the UK resettled more refugees from outside Europe than any other EU member state. In the year ending June 2019 the UK received 3,496 unaccompanied asylum-seeking children. In 2018, the UK received 15% of all asylum claims from unaccompanied children in the EU, representing the third highest intake country.</p><p>We remain absolutely committed to transferring the specified number of 480 unaccompanied children under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016 (Dubs Amendment) as soon as possible. We have been making further progress with participating States, including Greece, to transfer more eligible children to move closer to the commitment to transfer 480 children.</p><p>Until the UK leaves the EU, we remain fully committed to the timely and efficient operation of the Dublin III Regulation including the provisions determining responsibility for examining the claims of unaccompanied asylum-seeking children. Officials continue to work closely with Member States, including partners in Greece, to ensure the safe transfer of children under this Regulation.</p><p>Under Section 17 of the European Union (Withdrawal) Act, we are committed to seek to negotiate an agreement with the EU allowing for the family re-union of unaccompanied asylum-seeking children, where it is in their best interests, once we leave the EU. We are ready to engage with the EU and with Member States on this matter and will endeavour to negotiate such an agreement as soon as possible.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2019-11-04T17:49:38.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150625/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150625/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150625/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-17","Asylum: Greek Islands","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to support the resettlement of vulnerable children and unaccompanied minors from the Greek Islands.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150626","Home Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>This is a matter for the Foreign and Commonwealth Office. My team has passed it on to the FCO to respond to you.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2019-11-05T17:46:53.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150626/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150626/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-17","Asylum: Greece","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans, if any, they have to evacuate critically ill children from Greece whose access to adequate and timely healthcare services in that country is obstructed by their migrant status.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150627","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Greek Government is responsible for supporting migrants on arrival in Greece, including healthcare for unaccompanied minors. The EU has allocated over €2 billion since 2015 to support Greek handling of migration and border management. The United Kingdom is also providing bilateral support. This includes, in 2019, funding a shelter for the most vulnerable unaccompanied children who arrive in Samos. In addition, under Section 67 of the 2016 Immigration Act (the &quot;Dubs Amendment&quot;) the United Kingdom is accepting the transfer of some of the most vulnerable unaccompanied children from Greece.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-10-31T15:06:39.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150627/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150627/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-17","Greece: Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps, if any, they are taking to ensure the provision of essential healthcare and mental healthcare for unaccompanied minors in Greece.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150628","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-31","<p>​We do not currently have any plans to consult with Médecins Sans Frontières.</p><p>The UK will continue to work closely with the French authorities, our international partners, and local stakeholders on this issue, as underpinned by the Sandhurst Treaty. This makes specific provision for improving conditions for migrants in France, including facilitating the transfer of unaccompanied minors to the UK under national relocation schemes and improving access to French domestic asylum procedures.</p><p>We remain committed to engaging actively in shaping the international response on migration.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-10-31T15:33:13.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150628/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150628/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150628/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-17","France: Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to consult Médecins Sans Frontières about the ways in which healthcare for unaccompanied asylum-seeking young people in France can be improved, including psycho-social support.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150629","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-10-31","<p>Defra produces annual estimates of horticultural crop production. These estimates include tonnage, value and imports/exports which allow the Government to monitor productivity and competitiveness within the industry including supply and self-sufficiency. No estimates are made for the tonnage of crops left unharvested for any reason. As a result, no data is available to answer this question.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2019-10-31T15:06:05.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150629/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150629/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150629/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-10-17","Agriculture: Seasonal Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what estimate they have made of the tonnage of UK fruit and vegetables that were not harvested and left in the fields as a result of a shortage of seasonal workers.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150630","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-10-29","<p>We consulted on our proposals to reform the UK packaging producer responsibility system earlier this year. Based on the feedback we received and the strong support from respondents for the principles and outcomes proposed, we intend to progress these policy proposals and introduce an extended producer responsibility scheme for packaging in 2023. As is the case for the current system, the reformed system will target all packaging materials, including plastic.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2019-10-29T12:54:34.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150630/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150630/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150630/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-10-17","Plastics: Packaging","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they intend to introduce extended producer responsibility charges for manufactures producing plastic packaging.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150631","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-10-29","<p>At Budget 2018, the Government announced its intention to introduce a world-leading new tax on businesses that produce or import plastic packaging containing less than 30% recycled content, taking effect from April 2022. The tax will be set at a rate that provides a clear economic incentive for businesses to use recycled material in the production of plastic packaging. This will help to drive the treatment of plastic waste up the waste hierarchy so that more plastic is recycled rather than being sent to landfill or incineration.</p><p> </p><p>The tax will create demand for recycled plastic and will be supported by our reforms of the current packaging producer responsibility system, which will help to create a supply of recycled plastic material. We will introduce an extended producer responsibility system for packaging, which incentivises businesses to design packaging that is easy to recycle. These measures will help deliver our Resources and Waste Strategy, published last December, which sets out how we will recycle more plastic than we do now by moving to a more circular economy.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2019-10-29T13:16:38.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150631/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150631/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150631/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-10-17","Plastics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to prevent the increased use of virgin plastics in products as a result of the rise in the cost of recycled plastic flakes.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150632","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-24","<p>​On 16 October, Department for International Development Director General Moazzam Malik met Finance Minister Ncube at the World Bank and International Monetary Fund annual meetings in New York to discuss the economic and humanitarian crisis in Zimbabwe. He stressed that comprehensive political and economic reform, and commitment to respect for human rights and the rule of law, are prerequisites for Zimbabwe’s reengagement with the international community. The UK Ambassador met Foreign Minister Moyo on 18 October and discussed the economic crisis facing the country, reinforcing the need for comprehensive political and economic reform and the protection of the poorest.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-10-24T12:26:11.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150632/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150632/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150632/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-17","Zimbabwe: Economic Situation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they last met with the government of Zimbabwe at ministerial level to discuss the economic crisis in that country.","false","Biography information for Lord Oates",,"Lord Oates","HL208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150633","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-24","<p>The UK regularly discusses the economic situation in Zimbabwe with our international partners, including the EU, US and South Africa. In October, at the World Bank and International Monetary Fund annual meetings in New York, the UK met international partners including the USA, France and Germany to discuss economic and political reform in Zimbabwe. We have been clear that comprehensive political and economic reform must be delivered before the UK and our international partners will discuss arrears clearance with the Government of Zimbabwe.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL210 ; HL211","2019-10-24T12:28:09.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150633/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150633/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150633/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-17","Zimbabwe: Economic Situation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions they have had with the government of South Africa about the economic crisis in Zimbabwe.","false","Biography information for Lord Oates",,"Lord Oates","HL209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150634","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-24","<p>The UK regularly discusses the economic situation in Zimbabwe with our international partners, including the EU, US and South Africa. In October, at the World Bank and International Monetary Fund annual meetings in New York, the UK met international partners including the USA, France and Germany to discuss economic and political reform in Zimbabwe. We have been clear that comprehensive political and economic reform must be delivered before the UK and our international partners will discuss arrears clearance with the Government of Zimbabwe.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL209 ; HL211","2019-10-24T12:28:09.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150634/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150634/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150634/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-17","Zimbabwe: Economic Situation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions they have had with the EU about the economic crisis in Zimbabwe.","false","Biography information for Lord Oates",,"Lord Oates","HL210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150635","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-24","<p>The UK regularly discusses the economic situation in Zimbabwe with our international partners, including the EU, US and South Africa. In October, at the World Bank and International Monetary Fund annual meetings in New York, the UK met international partners including the USA, France and Germany to discuss economic and political reform in Zimbabwe. We have been clear that comprehensive political and economic reform must be delivered before the UK and our international partners will discuss arrears clearance with the Government of Zimbabwe.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL209 ; HL210","2019-10-24T12:28:09.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150635/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150635/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150635/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-17","Zimbabwe: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions they have had with any international partners about political and economic reform in Zimbabwe, and bilateral and multilateral financing for that country.","false","Biography information for Lord Oates",,"Lord Oates","HL211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150636","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-31","<p>The Northern Ireland Executive was not restored by 21 October 2019, so section 9 of the Northern Ireland (Executive Formation etc) Act 2019 has now come into force, providing for the decriminalisation of abortion in Northern Ireland in relation to sections 58 and 59 of the Offences Against the Person Act 1861. The United Kingdom Government is now under a duty to bring forward regulations to introduce a new legal framework for abortion in Northern Ireland by 31 March 2020 and has published guidance for healthcare professionals in Northern Ireland on abortion law for the period 22 October 2019 to 31 March 2020. This makes clear that abortion services are not expected to be routinely available in Northern Ireland before 31 March 2020.</p><p>The UK Government-funded Central Booking System (CBS) has been in operation since March 2018 as a single point of contact for women in Northern Ireland to access abortion care in England. The CBS, and abortion care provided under the scheme, will continue to offer the same service and care package to women from Northern Ireland between 22 October 2019 and 31 March 2020. During this period women from Northern Ireland will be able to have all travel and, where needed, accommodation paid for without any means testing. The package of care offered to women from Northern Ireland is equivalent to the package of care offered to women from England and includes a consultation including impartial information/advice, and where needed, counselling with an abortion provider in England.</p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford",,"2019-10-31T14:18:57.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150636/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150636/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150636/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-17","Abortion: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether women in Northern Ireland considering an abortion between 22 October 2019 and 31 March 2020 will be offered counselling equivalent to that offered to women in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Baroness O'Loan",,"Baroness O'Loan","HL212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150637","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-10-28","<p>The health and safety of women and girls, and clarity and certainty for the medical profession, is at the forefront of the Government’s approach in complying with the legal duty under section 9 of the Northern Ireland (Executive Formation etc) Act 2019.</p><p> </p><p>As the duty has now come into effect, there have been some immediate changes to the law in Northern Ireland. We do not expect there to be any additional services available ahead of the new legal framework being in place by 31 March 2020. It is important that we get the legal framework right and are confident that service provision in Northern Ireland can meet women and girls’ needs.</p><p> </p><p>In the meantime, women and girls resident in Northern Ireland will be able to continue to access services in England, with all costs of the procedure, including travel and, where needed, accommodation, being paid for from 22 October 2019.</p><p> </p><p>Healthcare professionals who have a conscientious objection should follow guidance from their professional body. We recognise that this is a sensitive issue, and consideration is being given to providing for conscientious objection in the new legal framework for access to abortion in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will be shortly consulting on this proposed framework.</p>",,"Lord Duncan of Springbank","HL214 ; HL215","2019-10-28T15:58:58.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150637/answer","Biography information for Lord Duncan of Springbank","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150637/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150637/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2019-10-17","Abortion: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how they will ensure that women's safety and well-being are protected should decriminalisation of abortion in Northern Ireland lead to unregulated abortions.","false","Biography information for Baroness O'Loan",,"Baroness O'Loan","HL213"
